The trunk or stem of a tree, or that which is like it.Enormous elm-tree boles did stoop and lean. Tennyson.
Prolonged at the base, as certain leaves.
In a running or hasty manner; carelessly.
A writer of glosses or of a glossary; a commentator; ascholiast. Tyrwhitt.
One of a sect of ancient Christians, who, in supposed imitationof the first believers, renounced all their possessions.
Woody. [Obs.] Skelton.
See Sequin.
To sprinkle with, or as with, stars; to decorate with, or aswith, stars; to bestud. "Bestarred with anemones." W. Black.
The Angora goat. See Angora goat, under Angora.
Opinionated. [Obs.]
Petty theft. [Scot.] Holinshed.
Hard; inflexible; obstinate; sour in aspect; hardy; bold.[Scot.]A dour wife, a sour old carlin. C. Reade.
A genus of plants, one species of which (A. Mexicanum) haslavender-blue flowers in dense clusters.

"A wooden pin stuck anciently on the sides of the bedstead, tohold the clothes from slipping on either side." Johnson.Hostess, accommodate us with a bedstaff. B. Jonson.Say there is no virtue in cudgels and bedstaves. Brome.
Full of gladness; joyful; glad. [R.] -- Glad"ful*ness, n. [R.]Spenser.It followed him with gladful glee. Spenser.
A nitrogenous substance, C8H7NO, isomeric with oxindol,obtained as an oily liquid.
Nihility; nothingness. [R.]
To growl; to snarl.And wolves are gnarling who shall gnaw thee first. Shak.
Peerless; incomparable. [Obs.] Spenser.
To bear sway over.
To follow closely, or so as to overtake; to pursue. [Obs.]To follow and detain him, if by any possibility he could besubsecuted and overtaken. E. Hall.
A variety of bacterium; a microscopic, rod-shaped vegetableorganism.
One who rejoices.
A sigh or sobbing; also, a hiccough. [Obs.] Spenser. W. Browne.
Made by complete closure of the mouth organs; shut; -- said ofcertain consonants (p, b, t, d, etc.). H. Sweet.
Passing to the west.Toward heaven's descent had sloped his westering wheel. Milton.
A native of China; a Chinese.
The fold of skin which covers the glans of the penis; theprepuce.
One who overlooks.
Methyl alcohol, CH3OH; -- also, by extension, any one in thehomologous series of paraffine alcohols of which methyl alcohol isthe type.

Openly declared, avowed, acknowledged, or claimed; as, aprofessed foe; a professed tyrant; a professed Christian. Theprofessed (R. C. Ch.) , a certain class among the Jesuits bound by aspecial vow. See the note under Jesuit.
Belonging to the Aplacentata; without placenta.
An oath.
One of the followers of Lucifer, bishop of Cagliari, in thefourth century, who separated from the orthodox churches because theywould not go as far as he did in opposing the Arians.
A commercial name for green aniline dye.
In a stagnant manner.

The part of a ship which is ordinarily under water; hence, thevessel itself; a ship.My ventures are not in one bottom trusted. Shak.Not to sell the teas, but to return them to London in the samebottoms in which they were shipped. Bancroft.Full bottom, a hull of such shape as permits carrying a large amountof merchandise.
Without a carpet.
The reed bunting. It has a collar of white feathers. Calledalso ring bunting.
Excessively greedy.
Moving with a bound or bounds.The bounding pulse, the languid limb. Montgomery.
The state of being devoted, or set apart by a vow. [R.] Bp.Hurd.
A method of taking photographic pictures, on paper sensitizedwith iodide of silver; -- also called Talbotype, from the inventor,Mr. Fox. Talbot.
Two pieces of bread and butter with a thin slice of meat,cheese, or the like, between them.

The chips or fragments made by boring. Boring bar, a revolvingor stationary bar, carrying one or more cutting tools for dressinground holes.-- Boring tool (Metal Working), a cutting tool placed in a cutterhead to dress round holes. Knight.

In Ireland, a lord or proprietor of a tract of land or of acastle, elected by a family, under the system of tanistry.This family [the O'Hanlons] were tanists of a large territory withinthe present county of Armagh. M. A. Lower.
The platform about the head of the mainmast in square-riggedvessels.

To make numb; to deprive of the power of sensation or motion;to render senseless or inert; to deaden; to benumb; to stupefy.For lazy winter numbs the laboring hand. Dryden.Like dull narcotics, numbing pain. Tennyson.
An earnest; earnest money; money paid to bind a bargain.[Scot.] Arles penny, earnest money given to servants. Kersey.

An instrument for recording, preserving, and reproducingsounds, the record being a tracing of a phonautograph etched in somesolid material. Reproduction  is accomplished by means of a systemattached to an elastic diaphragm.
Muddy; slimy; thick. Sir T. Browne.
Swallowing up. Wodhull.
The word is used as a Portuguese designation of money ofaccount, one hundred reis being about equal in value to eleven cents.
The light elastic wood of the Aspidosperma excelsum, a tree ofGuiana having a fluted trunk readily split into planks.
To call by a wrong title.
The business of making or managing rafts.
Having many faces.
Made or contrived for getting small sums of money from theignorant or unwary; as, a catchpenny book; a catchpenny show.-- n.
A country seat; a country or suburban residence of somepretensions to elegance. Dryden. Cowper.
One who uses, or is skilled in the use of, an oar; a rower.
Suitableness; agreement. [Obs.] hak.
A genus of leguminous herbs with densely spiked flowers andusually trifoliate leaves; trefoil. There are many species, all ofwhich are called clover. See Clover.
To make glib. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
Hastily; immediately; instantly; on the spot; hotfloot. Gower.Custance have they taken anon, foothot. Chaucer.
An orphan. [Obs.] Udcll.
A transparent or translucent variety of common feldspar, ororthoclase, which often shows pearly opalescent reflections; --called by lapidaries moonstone.
Having an air or manner characteristic of the stage;theatrical; artificial; as, a stagy tone or bearing; --chiefly useddepreciatively.
One who utters a shriek.

Primarily, liberty of converse; intercourse; hence, acertificate, given after compliance with quarantine regulations,permitting a ship to land passengers and crew; -- a term usedparticularly in the south of Europe.
To hie. [Obs.]Men must high them apace, and make haste. Holland.
A man whose occupation is to make malt.
One of the States of the United States of America.-- a.
Liable to be lost. [R.]
A periodical work published once a quarter, or four times in ayear.
A sea god in the service of Neptune who assumed differentshapes at will. Hence, one who easily changes his appearance orprinciples.
The act or process of retenting; the state of having relented.Sir T. Browne.
A short bar used by thieves to wrench doors open. [Written alsobettee.]The powerful betty, or the artful picklock. Arbuthnot.
A stranger. [Obs.] Spenser.
To jumble together.
Random. [Obs.] Spenser.
In a clumsy manner.
To exclude from participation in; to excommunicate. [Obs.]Poets . . . were excommuned Plato's common wealth Gayton.
To bully. [Obs.]She shan't think to bullock and domineer over me. Foote.
Earlier form of Acknow. [Obs.] To be aknow, to acknowledge; toconfess. [Obs.]
Of or pertaining to the gyrostat or to gyrostatics.
Of or pertaining to the thigh or leg, or to any of the partscalled crura; as, the crural arteries; crural arch; crural canal;crural ring.
The first word of any page of a book after the first, insertedat the right hand bottom corner of the preceding page for theassistance of the reader. It is seldom used in modern printing.
See Pasha.
To perish. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A semibreve. [R.]
Lubric.
Made friends; reconciled. [Obs.] "Deadly foes . . .affriended." Spenser.
The epithelial lining of the ventricles of the brain and thecanal of the spinal cord; endyma; ependymis.
To deliver up by one government to another, as a fugitive fromjustice. See Extradition.
To be overbusy or unduly anxious about trifles; to make abustle or ado. Sir W. Scott.
A smart, ready, and witty reply.Cupid was as bad as he; Hear but the youngster's repartee. Prior.
Angulous. [R.]
In a trusty manner.
One who annuls. [R.]
The original native name for the ancient Ethiopic language orpeople. See Ethiopic.
A building up; construction. [Obs.] Cockeram.
A blowing together, as of many instruments in a concert, or ofmany fires in a foundry. [R.]  Bacon.
A great brazen laver in the temple at Jerusalem; -- so calledfrom its size.He made a molten sea of ten cubits from brim to brim, round incompass, and five cubits the height thereof. 2 Chron. iv. 2.
An African genet (Genetta pardina). See Genet.
Standardized; determined or analyzed by titration; as, titratedsolutions.
A dry, cold, violent, northerly wind of the Adriatic.
After the manner of the Japanese; resembling japanned articles.Carlyle.
A young hog.
A joint cause. Fotherby.
The glycerin salt of ricinoleic acid, occuring as acharacteristic constituent of castor oil; -- formerly called palmin.

Any device in which an imperfectly conducting contact betweenpieces of metal or other conductors loosely resting against eachother is materially improved in conductivity by the influence ofHertzian waves; -- so called by Sir O. J. Lodge in 1894 on theassumption that the impact of the electic waves caused the looselyconnected parts to cohere, or weld together, a condition easilydestroyed by tapping. A common form of coherer as used in wirelesstelegraphy consists of a tube containing filings (usually a pinch ofnickel and silver filings in equal parts) between terminal wires orplugs (called conductor plugs).

Being of a bright saffronlike color; of the color of gold orbrass; having the hue of that part of the rainbow, or of the solarspectrum, which is between the orange and the green.Her yellow hair was browded [braided] in a tress. Chaucer.A sweaty reaper from his tillage brought First fruits, the green earand the yellow sheaf. Milton.The line of yellow light dies fast away. Keble.Yellow atrophy (Med.), a fatal affection of the liver, in which itundergoes fatty degeneration, and becomes rapidly smaller and of adeep yellow tinge. The marked symptoms are black vomit, delirium,convulsions, coma, and jaundice.-- Yellow bark, calisaya bark.-- Yellow bass (Zoöl.), a North American fresh-water bass (Moroneinterrupta) native of the lower parts of the Mississippi and itstributaries. It is yellow, with several more or less broken blackstripes or bars. Called also barfish.-- Yellow berry. (Bot.) Same as Persian berry, under Persian.-- Yellow boy, a gold coin, as a guinea. [Slang] Arbuthnot.-- Yellow brier. (Bot.) See under Brier.-- Yellow bugle (Bot.), a European labiate plant (Ajuga Chamæpitys).-- Yellow bunting (Zoöl.), the European yellow-hammer.-- Yellow cat (Zoöl.), a yellow catfish; especially, the bashaw.-- Yellow copperas (Min.), a hydrous sulphate of iron; -- calledalso copiapite.-- Yellow copper ore, a sulphide of copper and iron; copper pyrites.See Chalcopyrite.-- Yellow cress (Bot.), a yellow-flowered, cruciferous plant(Barbarea præcox), sometimes grown as a salad plant.-- Yellow dock. (Bot.) See the Note under Dock.-- Yellow earth, a yellowish clay, colored by iron, sometimes usedas a yellow pigment.-- Yellow fever (Med.), a malignant, contagious, febrile disease ofwarm climates, attended with jaundice, producing a yellow color ofthe skin, and with the black vomit. See Black vomit, in theVocabulary.-- Yellow flag, the quarantine flag. See under Quarantine, and 3dFlag.-- Yellow jack. (a) The yellow fever. See under 2d Jack. (b) Thequarantine flag. See under Quarantine.-- Yellow jacket (Zoöl.), any one of several species of Americansocial wasps of the genus Vespa, in which the color of the body ispartly bright yellow. These wasps are noted for their irritability,and for their painful stings.-- Yellow lead ore (Min.), wulfenite.-- Yellow lemur (Zoöl.), the kinkajou.-- Yellow macauco (Zoöl.), the kinkajou.-- Yellow mackerel (Zoöl.), the jurel.-- Yellow metal. Same as Muntz metal, under Metal.-- Yellow ocher (Min.), an impure, earthy variety of brown iron ore,which is used as a pigment.-- Yellow oxeye (Bot.), a yellow-flowered plant (Chrysanthemumsegetum) closely related to the oxeye daisy.-- Yellow perch (Zoöl.), the common American perch. See Perch.-- Yellow pike (Zoöl.), the wall-eye.-- Yellow pine (Bot.), any of several kinds of pine; also, theiryellowish and generally durable timber. Among the most common arevaluable species are Pinus mitis and P. palustris of the Eastern andSouthern States, and P. ponderosa and P. Arizonica of the RockyMountains and Pacific States.-- Yellow plover (Zoöl.), the golden plover.-- Yellow precipitate (Med. Chem.), an oxide of mercury which isthrown down as an amorphous yellow powder on adding corrosivesublimate to limewater.-- Yellow puccoon. (Bot.) Same as Orangeroot.-- Yellow rail (Zoöl.), a small American rail (PorzanaNoveboracensis) in which the lower parts are dull yellow, darkest onthe breast. The back is streaked with brownish yellow and with black,and spotted with white. Called also yellow crake.-- Yellow rattle, Yellow rocket. (Bot.) See under Rattle, andRocket.-- Yellow Sally (Zoöl.), a greenish or yellowish European stone flyof the genus Chloroperla; -- so called by anglers.-- Yellow sculpin (Zoöl.), the dragonet.-- Yellow snake (Zoöl.), a West Indian boa (Chilobothrus inornatus)common in Jamaica. It becomes from eight to ten long. The body isyellowish or yellowish green, mixed with black, and anteriorly withblack lines.-- Yellow spot. (a) (Anat.) A small yellowish spot with a centralpit, the fovea centralis, in the center of the retina where vision ismost accurate. See Eye. (b) (Zoöl.) A small American butterfly(Polites Peckius) of the Skipper family. Its wings are brownish, witha large, irregular, bright yellow spot on each of the hind wings,most conspicuous beneath. Called also Peck's skipper. See Illust.under Skipper, n., 5.-- Yellow tit (Zoöl.), any one of several species of crested titmiceof the genus Machlolophus, native of India. The predominating colorsof the plumage are yellow and green.-- Yellow viper (Zoöl.), the fer-de-lance.-- Yellow warbler (Zoöl.), any one of several species of Americanwarblers of the genus Dendroica in which the predominant color isyellow, especially D. æstiva, which is a very abundant and familiarspecies; -- called also garden warbler, golden warbler, summeryellowbird, summer warbler, and yellow-poll warbler.-- Yellow wash (Pharm.), yellow oxide of mercury suspended in water,-- a mixture prepared by adding corrosive sublimate to limewater.-- Yellow wren (Zoöl.) (a) The European willow warbler. (b) TheEuropean wood warbler.
A piece of canvas fastened by lacing to the bonnet of a sail,to give it a greater depth, or more drop.
In an icy manner; coldly.Faultily faultless, icily regular, splendidly null, Dead perfection,no more. Tennyson.
Each player's stake, which is put into the pool before (ante)the game begins.
A hanger-on.
A term formerly given to the salts supposed to be formedrespectively by neutralizing acids with certain peroxides. [Obsoles.]
To convert into, or make, good.To bonify evils, or tincture them with good. Cudworth.
To cover with shade; to render dark or gloomy; to overshadow.Shak.
The llama.
One who taws; a dresser of white leather.
A bitter, white, crystalline substance found in orange andlemon seeds.
See Chrysoberyl.
Bipolar quality.
A stock or handle for holding and rotating a bit; a brace.
Having the nose broad; -- opposed to Ant: leptorhine.-- n. (Zoöl.)
A piggin. [Written also pigg.]
The quality or state of being prefident. [Obs.] Baxter.
Whatever pertains to the subject under consideration; allthings.More wise, more learned, more just, more everything. Pope.
Like wood.
The dried meat of the cocoanut, from which cocoanut oil isexpressed. [Written also cobra, copperah, coppra.]
Quality or state of being pink.
In an acute manner; sharply; keenly; with nice discrimination.
Of or in the Christian church or era, anterior to the firstcouncil of Nice, held a. d. 325; as, antenicene faith.
Employed in, or designed for, exploration. "Exploring parties."Bancroft.
To tell, rehearse, or recite, as a story; to relate theparticulars of; to go through with in detail, as an incident ortransaction; to give an account of.
The office or dignity of a doge.
A kind of whip for flogging criminals, formerly much used inRussia. The last is a tapering bundle of leather thongs twisted withwire and hardened, so that it mangles the flesh.

A place for keeping things in safety. Specifically:(a) A strong and fireproof receptacle (as a movable chest of steel,etc., or a closet or vault of brickwork) for money, valuable papers,or the like.(b) A ventilated or refrigerated chest or closet for securingprovisions from noxious animals or insects.
The oxide, Y2O3, or earth, of yttrium.
A porridge or gruel of maize meal and water, milk, or the like.[Sp. Amer.]
Same as Eisel. [Obs.] Shak.
The blue titmouse. [Prov. Eng.]
Of, pertaining to, or derived from, the celandine. Cheidonicacid, a weak acid extracted fron the celandine (Chelidonium majus),as a white crystalline substance.
An earthen vessel wider at the top than at the bottom, -- usedfor holding milk and for various other purposes. [Prov. Eng.]Halliwell.
Such. [Obs. or Colloq.] Spenser.
One who, or that which, infuses.
Somewhat sweet; sweetish. [R.]

An ethereal salt, or compound ether, consisting of an organicradical united with the residue of any oxygen acid, organic orinorganic; thus the natural fats are esters of glycerin and the fattyacids, oleic, etc.
A diseased condition produced by slow poisoning with arsenic.
To reach or extend over.
Belonging to antipathy; opposite; contrary; allopathic.
Serving to discover or find out.

Having length; rather long or too long; prolix; not brief; --said chiefly of discourses, writings, and the like. "Lengthyperiods." Washington. "Some lengthy additions." Byron. "These wouldbe details too lengthy." Jefferson. "To cut short lengthyexplanations." Trench.
Standing out of, or rising above, water. Gray.
A Linnæan class of plants in which the stamens are united bythe anthers.
Having no veil. Tennyson.
To take by assault; to storm; to overcome; to vanquish; as, toexpugn cities; to expugn a person by arguments.
A place or establishment where flax is retted. See Ret. Ure.
To drive out; to expel. [Obs.]If charity be thus excluded and expulsed. Milton.
Gathering, or dredging for, oysters.
A person affected with paralysis.
Sick at heart; extremely depressed in spirits; very despondent.
Soiled; sullied; of a dark or dusky color; dark brown; dirty."Scraps of dingy paper." Macaulay.
An island in a river; an ait. [Obs.] "Osiers on their eights."Evelyn.
Destitute of fire.
Furnished with leaves; leafy; as, a foliate stalk. Foliatecurve. (Geom.) Same as Folium.
Aromatic. [Obs.] Caxton.
To become open, disclosed, or developed; to pass through aprocess of evolution. Prior.
Same as Ligan. Brande & C.
Linear. Holland.

A name applied to various marine univalve shells; esp. to thoseof the genus Strombus, which are of large size. S. gigas is the largepink West Indian conch. The large king, queen, and cameo conchs areof the genus Cassis. See Cameo.

Any instrument showing the changes in the weight of theatmosphere; also, less appropriately, any instrument that indicates -or foreshadows changes of the weather, as a deep vial of liquidholding in suspension some substance which rises and falls withatmospheric changes.
A bird having small polygonal scales covering the tarsi.
One who works in tin; a tinner.
To err in pleading.
See Wormil.
Marked with parallel or radiating lines.
One skilled in the knowledge of plants; a collector of, ordealer in, herbs, especially medicinal herbs.
The native name of certain South American monkeys of the genusAteles, esp. A. paniscus. The black-faced coaita is Ateles ater. SeeIllustration in Appendix.
Biting; pinching; painful; destructive; as, a nipping frost; anipping wind.
An exclamation formerly used as an oath, and an expression ofanger or wonder.
In sport; sportively.The question you there put, you do it, I suppose, but sportingly.Hammond.
A small worm or insect larva; also, a wormlike body. [R.]Derham.
A performer on the flute; a flautist. Busby.
Made of jet, or like jet in color.The people . . . are of a jetty. Sir T. Browne.

Excessive vanity excited by one's own performances; emptypride; undue elation of mind; vain show; boastfulness.He had nothing of vainglory. Bacon.The man's undone forever; for if Hector break not his neck i' thecombat, he'll break't himself in vainglory. Shak.
See Spilikin.
A small abscess or tumor having a resemblance to a mulberry.Dunglison.
The green woodpecker, or yaffle. See Yaffle. [Prov. Eng.]
To free from being inclosed.

Pertaining to fulminic and cyanuric acids, and designating anacid so called. Fulminuric acid (Chem.), a white, crystalline,explosive subatance, H3C3N3O3, forming well known salts, and obtainedfrom the fulnunates. It is isomeric with cyanuric acid, and hence isalso called isocyanuric acid.
A person of modern times; -- opposed to ancient. Pope.
Remorse; compunction; compassion. [Obs.] Killingbeck.
A lock of wool hanging under the belly of a sheep.
Falling or turned downward; reclinate.
The privy parts; the genitals.Ham ... saw the nakedness of his father. Gen. ix. 22.
To put in action. [Obs.]
The pewit gull.
The most elevated part of a bivalve shell, or the part in whichthe hinge is situated. Summit level, the highest level of a canal, arailroad, or the like, in surmounting an ascent.
Same as Rhomb, 1.

A series of antiphons and responses, expressing the sorrowfulremonstrance of our Lord with his people; -- sung on the morning ofthe Good Friday in place of the usual daily Mass of the Roman ritual.Grove.
The quality or state of being squalid; foulness; filthiness.
Having the anterior surface of the tarsus covered withscutella, or transverse scales, in the form of incomplete bandsterminating at a groove on each side; -- said of certain birds.
One skilled in pharmacy; a pharmaceutist; a druggist.

Uplifted; high; lofty; also, animated; noble; as, elevatedthoughts. Elevated railway, one in which the track is raisedconsiderably above the ground, especially a city railway above theline of street travel.
The figure, statue, or bust, on the prow of a ship.
Frequent; numerous. [Obs.] Goodwin.
Descendants of the human kind, or offspring of other animals;children; offspring; race, lineage. " Issued from the progeny ofkings." Shak.
Judea; also, a district inhabited by Jews; a Jews' quarter.Chaucer.Teaching throughout all Jewry. Luke xxiii. 5.
A kind of tape or braid. Shak.
Of or pertaining to croup; resembling or indicating croup; as,a croupy cough.
One who dissuades; a dehorter.
Absent-minded; lost in thought; abstracted.
of Mote. Chaucer.
Same as Tremando.
Containing repetition; repeating. [R.]
Copper sulphide, used to color glass. Hebert.
So as to heal or cure.
Captious; testy. [Written also teatish.] [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
Not believed; disbelieved.
To reck; to care. [Obs.] Shak.
One who revels. "Moonshine revelers." Shak.
An hypogynous plant.
A choliamb.
To insert as in a sheath; to sheathe. Hughes.
A Roman governor of the fourth part of a province; hence, anysubordinate or dependent prince; also, a petty king or sovereign.
A snatching away. [Obs.]
The burning of a wad of pease straw at the end of harvest.[Prov. Eng.]
A name in the East Indies and the Indian islands for all ardentspirits. Arrack is often distilled from a fermented mixture of rice,molasses, and palm wine of the cocoanut tree or the date palm, etc.
To go or move upward upon or along; to climb; to mount; to goup the top of; as, to ascend a hill, a ladder, a tree, a river, athrone.

A hut or small cottage in an expessed or a retired place (as ona mountain or at the seaside) such as is used by shepherds,fishermen, sportsmen, etc.; a summer cottage; also, a shed. [Writtenalso sheel, shealing, sheiling, etc.] [Scot.]

A curve invented by Diocles, for the purpose of solving twocelebrated problems of the higher geometry; viz., to trisect a planeangle, and to construct two geometrical means between two givenstraight lines.
Situated behind any transverse axis in the body of an animal;caudal; posterior; especially, behind, or on the caudal or posterior(that is, ulnar or fibular) side of, the axis of a vertebrate limb.
A fish spear. [Obs.] Ainsworth.
A female maker of, or dealer in, articles of fashion,especially of the fashionable dress of ladies; a woman who givesdirection to the style or mode of dress.
Of or pertaining to machines.
A fermented beverage made of honey and water; mead. Gay.
Full of ease; suitable for affording ease or rest; quiet;comfortable; restful. Shak.-- Ease"ful*ly, adv.-- Ease"ful*ness, n.
See Web, n., 8.
Slovenliness. [Obs.] Shak.

Pertaining to, or invented by, Brown; -- a term applied to asystem of medicine promulgated in the 18th century by John Brown, ofScotland, the fundamental doctrine of which was, that life is a stateof excitation produced by the normal action of external agents uponthe body, and that disease consists in excess or deficiency ofexcitation.

A suffix denoting that which does a thing; an act or process;the result of an act or process; state or condition; as, aliment,that which nourishes, ornament, increment; fragment, piece broken,segment; abridgment, act of abridging, imprisonment, movement,adjournment; amazement, state of being amazed, astonishment.
See Creatin.
A judicial court of chancery, which in England and in theUnited States is distinctively a court with equity jurisdiction.
One of the Cystidea.
To cultivate by planting simultaneous crops in alternate rows;as, to intercrop an orchard. Also, to use for catch crops at seasonswhen the ground is not covered by crops of the regular rotation.
To bury again. Ashmole.
To press again.
To bask in the sun. Boyle.
In a spicy manner.
Unequal; uneven; various. [Obs.] Chaucer.
The middle segment of the thorax in insects. See Illust. ofColeoptera.
See Pinkster.

Out of the neighborhood of; lessening or losing proximity to;leaving behind; by reason of; out of; by aid of; -- used wheneverdeparture, setting out, commencement of action, being, state,occurrence, etc., or procedure, emanation, absence, separation, etc.,are to be expressed. It is construed with, and indicates, the pointof space or time at which the action, state, etc., are regarded assetting out or beginning; also, less frequently, the source, thecause, the occasion, out of which anything proceeds; -- thearitithesis and correlative of to; as, it, is one hundred miles fromBoston to Springfield; he took his sword from his side; lightproceeds from the sun; separate the coarse wool from the fine; menhave all sprung from Adam, and often go from good to bad, and frombad to worse; the merit of an action depends on the principle fromwhich it proceeds; men judge of facts from personal knowledge, orfrom testimony.Experience from the time past to the time present. Bacon.The song began from Jove. Drpden.From high Mæonia's rocky shores I came. Addison.If the wind blow any way from shore. Shak.
A continuous noise or murmur.The chide of streams. Thomson.
Pertaining to, or like, augite; containing augite as aprincipal constituent; as, augitic rocks.

A constellation of the northern hemisphere, situated betweenCapheus and Perseus; -- so called in honor of the wife of Cepheus, afabuolous king of Ethiopia. Cassiopeia's Chair, a group of six stars,in Cassiopeia, somewhat resembling a chair.
To take to graze or pasture, at a certain sum; -- usedoriginally of the feeding of cattle in the king's forests, andcollecting the money for the same. Blackstone.
One who makes rhymes; a versifier; -- generally in contempt; apoor poet; a poetaster.This would make them soon perceive what despicaple creatures ourcommon rhymers and playwriters be. Milton.
See Bort.
Bearing fruit but once; monocarpic.
Of or pertaining to Judea.-- n.
To make fast, as a rope, by taking several turns with it rounda pin, cleat, or kevel. Totten.

Incapable of being conquered, overcome, or subdued;unconquerable; insuperable; as, an invincible army, or obstacle.Lead forth to battle these my sons Invincible. Milton.-- In*vin"ci*ble*ness, n.-- In*vin"ci*bly, adv.
An ambling nag. "An easy padnag." Macaulay.
